						<h2>What is a game server?</h2>
						<p><strong>A game server is a computer that acts as a central authority to define the current state of a multiplayer game.</strong></p>
						<p>Players send the server updates about what they’re doing in-game — and the server processes all inputs, settles inconsistencies, and transmits regular updates to players, providing a stream of snapshots of all elements in the game.</p>
						<img src="/img/content/what-is-a-game-server/game-server-players-hand-drawn-illustration.png" alt="A hand drawn diagram with a game server in the middle, connected to players on the outside, each sending and receiving data to the server" class="my-4">
						<p>A game server is both the stadium where the game is played — and it’s also the referee.</p>
						<p>If you’re playing a game, when you jump, your computer tells that to the server, and the server tells everyone else that you’re in the air.</p>
						<p>So how does everyone know what in-game “reality” is?</p>
						<p>To explain, we need to cover two key concepts: game state and tickrate.</p>
						<!-- Game State -->
						<h2 class="mt-4" id="game-state">Game state: the single source of truth</h2>
						<p><strong>The game state (or “tick”) is a snapshot in time of the properties of every object in the game world.</strong></p>
