						<p>While peer-to-peer games are cheaper for the developers (as they don’t have to buy dedicated servers), it usually isn’t great for players.</p>
						<p>Running both the game client and game server can be taxing — and if the “host” player has a bad internet connection, it can be a bad experience for everyone in the game.</p>
						<h2 class="mt-4">Where are game servers located?</h2>
						<p class="fail mt-8">Both peer-to-peer and hosting from a home computer use one player’s home network.</p>
						<p>Which means everyone relies on home internet of the host.</p>
						<p>In peer-to-peer, the networking will attempt the best connection, but the host’s location can skew the ping to the advantage of certain players.</p>
						<p>Servers that are run from data centres have a lot of benefits over these two kinds of hosting.</p>
						<p>Most importantly: they are designed for and built with hosting multiplayer games in mind.</p>
						<p>The best experience for gamers is either dedicated servers from the developer or hosting their own dedicated server in a data centre. </p>
						<p>But the connection to these servers isn’t instant. The time between your information being sent to the server, and the server being able to respond is called ping.</p>
